Experimenting With Life’s Fullest Potential

 

Who am I?

A young person seeking to understand what it means to be human. I am experimenting with life as much as I can. Beginning things, dropping projects, starting new endeavors, changing my mind, adopting new views — all while being focused and conscious. It’s not easy to understand what it means to be human but I believe it’s important to persistently try to find it.

A few keywords that describe me

Degrowth, Sustainable Consumption, Sustainable Development, Optimism, Positivism, Happiness, Voluntary Simplicity, Minimalism, Solus Project, Linux, Open-Source Software, Acoustic Guitar, Podcasts, Storytelling, German, Polish, English, Dutch, Spanish.

Why this website and how to contact me?

This website is primarily for myself to help me remember the answers to the questions I keep asking myself repeatedly. If they did answer your questions as well or spark new ideas, then I would love to hear from you by email (hint: see above in the title)!

What do I identify with?

I identify myself through the activities I do regularly. Currently, my main profession is user satisfaction and experience at Sheetgo, a startup that helps people work with more accurate information thanks to connected spreadsheets. Aside, I approve video subtitles for the Amara foundation. I help the Solus Project with translation, bug reports and feature discussions. I assist Research & Degrowth and SCORAI with the diffusion of degrowth and sustainable consumption. I listen to a few good podcasts, coordinate the Vocabulary Degrowth Audiobook Podcast, and from time to time record my own podcasts.

What are small life hacks I really like?

I believe one can tweak life through simple means and improve upon one’s own condition day by day:

  • •Thinking of the time allocation per day in a simple way like this: 

    1. 1.6:00 AM to 09:00 AM: your personal development 

    2. 2.09:00 AM to 17:00 PM: your professional development 

    3. 3.17:00 PM onward: your social development 

  • •Creating strong habits and routines. Improving on tiny things day by day. This means having a repetitive week from Monday to Friday to maintain a regular routine and create those strong habits; 

  • •Bookmarking websites in the bookmarks bar to check them day by day until I have the feeling I can archive them permanently into a bookmarks folder; 

  • •Trying to eat less and smaller amounts. Nowadays, we generally eat way too much than we need to; 

  • •Working at a standing desk; 

  • •Using earplugs when moving around the city to reduce the noise level and make me feel less stressed; 

  • •When sitting trying to not rely on the leaning of the chair to keep the spine straight and strong; 

  • •Maintaining a long-enough sleep cycle; 

  • •Making the weekend totally different from the habitual week; 

A small note on research

My co-authored publication “Culture meets Flows: The Cultural Dimension of Urban Metabolism” that had been cited by the German Advisory Council on Global Change (WBGU) in their report “Humanity on the move: Unlocking the transformative power of cities”.

What makes me curious at present?

I am trying to understand and make sense of my own consumption patterns. My goal is to minimize the number of rows in the below table and reduce my consumption to a minimum to keep my carbon footprint low and spend my limited time and financial resources wisely. I want to invest into the things I truly care about and ignore all the rest. To not only be a consumer but a producer and co-creator. I call this work-in-progress project the “Table of Regular Sustainable Consumption”.
